      "observed": "Learners observed three fully worked examples (Kimathi Street passport photo area, Kisumu githeri pot height ratio, Eldoret maize silo surface area) that modelled the complete LSF→ASF→VSF chain, and completed four mixed Kenyan-context problems independently and in pairs.",
      "learned": "Learners consolidated that LSF, ASF (= LSF²), and VSF (= LSF³) form a single unified system; that diagnosing which scale factor a problem provides — and which it demands — is the critical first step; and that the passport photographer's software preserves shape because every length is multiplied by the same LSF, keeping all angle ratios and length ratios constant.",
      "explained": "Learners explained in writing why the resized passport photo looks identical but occupies a different area: the LSF scales every length equally (preserving all proportions and angles), the area changes by LSF², and if the photo were three-dimensional the volume would change by LSF³ — demonstrating that one number, the Linear Scale Factor, governs the entire transformation."
