        "learnerExperience": "Learners receive the structured three-problem worksheet (one page, three clearly boxed problems). They work INDEPENDENTLY and in SILENCE for 18 minutes, showing all working. PROBLEM 1 — MAP (Linear/LSF): A map of Kenya uses a scale of 1 : 2 500 000. On the map, the distance from Nairobi to Nakuru is 5.8 cm. (a) Calculate the actual distance in kilometres. (b) A second, smaller map of the same region has a scale of 1 : 5 000 000. What is the distance from Nairobi to Nakuru on this smaller map? (c) What is the LSF of the second map relative to the first map? PROBLEM 2 — ROOFING AREA (ASF): An architect in Mombasa builds a scale model of a coastal villa. The model roof has an area of 450 cm². The LSF from model to real building is 1 : 25. (a) Calculate the area of the real roof in cm². (b) Convert this to m². (c) Roofing tiles cost Ksh 850 per m². What is the total cost of tiling the real roof? PROBLEM 3 — WATER TANK VOLUME (VSF): A Kericho tea farm uses two geometrically similar cylindrical water tanks. The smaller tank has a volume of 1 200 litres. The LSF from the smaller tank to the larger tank is 1 : 3. (a) Calculate the volume of the larger tank in litres. (b) Water costs Ksh 4.50 per litre to pump. How much more does it cost to fill the larger tank than the smaller tank? (c) A third tank is geometrically similar to the smaller tank with LSF = 1 : 1.5. What is its volume?",
        "teacherMoves": "Distribute worksheets. Say: 'This is individual silent work — it is your chance to show yourself what you know. You have 18 minutes. Begin.' Set timer visibly. Circulate continuously using a two-column clipboard: left column — learner name, right column — which problem they are on and any error observed (e.g., 'used LSF instead of LSF³ for volume'). Do NOT correct errors during circulation — only note them for use in the Explain phase. At the 15-minute mark say: 'Three minutes remaining — if you have not reached Problem 3, write what relationship you would use and why.' After 18 minutes: 'Pens down. Swap your worksheet with the person directly to your right — you will now peer-mark.'",
