        "teacherMoves": "Say: 'Open your model page. You are drawing your FINAL model — this is the full picture you have been building for 12 lessons. You have 8 minutes.' Circulate. After 8 minutes, project the side-by-side Day-1 vs. final model comparison. Say: 'Look at what you knew on Day 1 and what you know now.' Cold-call 3 learners: 'Tell me ONE thing your final model shows that your Day-1 model could not.' Allow 10 seconds wait time per response. Close the lesson by returning to the driving question one final time: 'Why does resizing a passport photo change its size but never its shape — and what is the mathematics that makes this possible?' Cold-call one learner to give the complete answer in 3–4 sentences. Affirm and summarise: 'The Linear Scale Factor — a single number — governs every length. Angles are preserved. Area scales by LSF². Volume scales by LSF³. That is the mathematics behind every perfectly resized image, every architect's model, and every similar figure you will ever meet.'",
